## 3. Rights That May Be Limited or Restricted

### 3.1 Loss of Liberty and Associated Rights

By definition, prisoners lose the right to liberty, including freedom of movement. Other rights, such as voting, may be restricted depending on jurisdiction and the nature of the offense ([Britannica](https://www.britannica.com/topic/prisoners-rights)).

### 3.2 Restrictions for Security and Order

Certain rights may be limited to maintain prison security and order, such as restrictions on communication or association. However, such restrictions must be necessary, proportionate, and subject to oversight ([Penal Reform International](https://www.penalreform.org/issues/prison-conditions/)).

---

## 4. Controversial and Emerging Issues

### 4.1 Voting Rights of Prisoners

The right to vote is widely recognized as fundamental in democratic societies. However, many countries restrict or deny voting rights to prisoners. The European Court of Human Rights has ruled against blanket bans, emphasizing the importance of proportionality and human dignity ([Legal Desire](https://legaldesire.com/human-rights-of-prisoners-international-national-perspectives/)).

### 4.2 Prison Labor

The imposition of forced labor is prohibited under international law. Prison labor must be voluntary, fairly compensated, and not exploitative. Recent proposals to require prisoners to pay for their incarceration or work excessive hours raise ethical and legal concerns ([Legal Desire](https://legaldesire.com/human-rights-of-prisoners-international-national-perspectives/)).

### 4.3 Protection of Vulnerable Prisoners

Certain groups, such as former law enforcement officers, sexual offenders, juveniles, and transgender individuals, require special protections to ensure safety and dignity. Solitary confinement, for example, should be used sparingly and not as routine protection ([Britannica](https://www.britannica.com/topic/prisoners-rights)).

